<section xml:id="sec_SigmaNotation_StudyGuide">
  <title>Study guide  for
  <q>Sigma Notation</q>
  chapter</title>
  <subsection>
    <title><xref ref="sec_SigmaNotation_Examples">Section</xref>, Lots of examples</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Concepts:</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Summation notion
            (sigma notation)
            <mdash/> <m>\Sigma</m> is the symbol used to denote summation it is called sigma
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Index variable <mdash/> variable used in the equation that will change and is located beneath the <m>\Sigma</m> symbol
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Starting value <mdash/> located below the <m>\Sigma</m> and is the value that begins the summation
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Final value <mdash/> located above the <m>\Sigma</m> and is the last value in the summation
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Formula <mdash/> located to the right of <m>\Sigma</m>,
                  which includes the variable, used to calculate the result
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Competencies</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Evaluate expressions given in summation notation.
            <xref ref="exercise_SigmaNotation_Sigma_Notation_Practice"/>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title><xref ref="sec_SigmaNotation_Properties">Section</xref>, Sigma notation properties</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Concepts:</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Addition and scalar multiplication of sums
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Changing the summation index without changing the sum <xref ref="exercise_SigmaNotation_sum1"/>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Key formulas</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Formulas for addition and scalar multiplication of sums:
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle{\sum_{i=a}^{b} c \cdot d_{i} = c \cdot \sum_{i=a}^{b} d_{i}}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle{\sum_{i=0}^{n} \left(x_{i} +y_{i} \right) = \sum_{i=0}^{n} x_{i} + \sum_{i=0}^{n} y_{i}}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle{\sum_{i=0}^{n} \left(c \cdot x_{i} + d \cdot y_{i} \right) = c \cdot \sum_{i=0}^{n} x_{i} + d \cdot \sum_{i=0}^{n} y_{i}}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Competencies</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Be able to change the starting value and formula of sigma notations and maintain the same results.
            <xref ref="exercise_SigmaNotation_sum1"/>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title><xref ref="sec_SigmaNotation_Nested">Section</xref>, Nested sigmas</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Concepts:</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Nested sigmas <mdash/> The entire sum of the inside sigma must be calculated for each value of the index of the outside sigma.
            <em>Note</em> that the index of the outer sum may appear in any or all parts of the inner sum.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Rearranging the order of summation <mdash/> exchange the order of the summations and adjust the limits.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Competencies</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Be able to exchange the order of sums and use other sum manipulation techniques to calculate values of summations. ( <xref ref="exercise_SigmaNotation_nested1"></xref>,
            <xref ref="exercise_SigmaNotation_nested2"></xref>)
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title><xref ref="sec_SigmaNotation_CommonSums">Section</xref>, Common Sums</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Concepts:</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Common summation formulas
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Geometric series <mdash/> sum of non-negative integer powers of a common base
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Key formulas</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle{\sum_{i = 1}^{k}i= \frac{k(k + 1)}{2}}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle{\sum_{i = a}^{k}i} = a + (a + 1) + (a + 2) + \cdots + (k - 1) + k = (k + a) * \frac{k - a + 1}{2}</m> where <m>a</m> and <m>k</m> are integers and <m>a\lt k</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <me>
              \sum_{i=0}^{n-1} ar^i = a \dfrac{1-r^n}{1-r}
            </me>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Competencies</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Be able to write the sum of given integers in sigma notation and give the formula for that sum.
            <xref ref="exercise_SigmaNotation_common1"/>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
